\par \u10095? \cf4 This is a solid update. You've incorporated the critical feedback: delta writes, work caps, version stamp, invariants, and safe division. The document is now much more\cf1 
\par \cf4   grounded, and the implementation stats (71 tests, 7.6k lines) show real progress.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   The core architecture is sound. The open questions are appropriate for Phase 2.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   A few remaining points to tighten before you dive into the "military camp kit" (or whatever comes next):\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 1. State growth \emdash  characters and armies\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   Your current model has no pruning for dead characters or disbanded armies. Over thousands of turns, the character list will grow (births > deaths) and army list may\cf1 
\par \cf4   accumulate if AI raises armies without disbanding.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   **Recommendation**: Add a lifecycle policy now, even if implementation is later.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   - **Characters**: After a character dies, keep a compact tombstone (id, name, dynasty, cause of death, prestige) for historical events, but remove the full record from the\cf1 
\par \cf4   active simulation vectors.\cf1 
\par \cf4   - **Armies**: When an army is destroyed (casualties > 0 and zero remaining troops) or manually disbanded, remove it from storage. Add a `MAX_ARMIES_PER_FACTION` (e.g., 5)\cf1 
\par \cf4   to prevent unbounded AI spamming.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   This is easy to model in the `DirtyTracker` (you already track added/removed armies). Without it, you risk gas creep and replay cost growth.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 2. Tick scheduler \emdash  needs a decision\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   You have `BLOCKS_PER_TURN = 10` but the scheduling logic lives outside the plugin. This is a critical integration point. Decide now whether ticks are\cf1 
\par \cf4   **block\u8209?height\u8209?triggered** or **timer\u8209?based**.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   - **Block\u8209?height\u8209?triggered** is simpler and deterministic.\cf1 
\par \cf4   - **Timer\u8209?based** decouples from block rate but introduces wall\u8209?clock dependence that must be resolved by the host (e.g., storing the last tick block and calculating\cf1 
\par \cf4   expected turn number).\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   I recommend sticking with **block\u8209?height\u8209?triggered** for the first version. It keeps determinism trivial and aligns with the blockchain's natural cadence.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 3. Checkpoint policy \emdash  pick one now\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   You have three options (every tick delta, periodic full, threshold\u8209?based). Choose one and implement it before you start writing heavy tests. The default should be\cf1 
\par \cf4   **threshold\u8209?based**: if `dirty_count() > total_entities / 2`, write a full snapshot; otherwise delta. This is simple, adaptive, and safe.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   The storage layer already supports both; you just need the decision logic in the tick handler.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 4. Birth system \emdash  define the scope\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   Your open question 7.3 asks good questions. For Phase 2, I'd suggest a **minimal birth system**:\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   - Married couples (both alive, age between 16 and 45) have a **fixed conception chance per turn** (e.g., 1/100).\cf1 
\par \cf4   - Child gets stats as **parent average + random noise** (using domain\u8209?separated RNG).\cf1 
\par \cf4   - Limit births per turn to `MAX_BIRTHS_PER_TURN` (5). If more couples are eligible, only the first N (by deterministic order) produce children.\cf1 
\par \cf4   - Child automatically joins father's dynasty (or mother's if matrilineal flag is set).\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   This is enough to test dynasty growth without overcomplicating. More complex inheritance (traits, education) can come later.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 5. Realm split \emdash  stub is fine for now\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   You already have the crisis detection and a `realm_split` boolean. The full province redistribution can be a Phase 2\u8209?specific task. Just ensure the stub doesn't cause an\cf1 
\par \cf4   unwrap or panic.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   ## 6. WASM gas metering \emdash  you need a real test\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   You have work caps, but the actual gas consumption of a full tick (including storage writes) is unknown. Once the delta persistence is wired, run a simulated turn on the\cf1 
\par \cf4   target VM (wasmer/wasmi) with gas metering enabled. Measure both a quiet turn and a worst\u8209?case turn (max battles, events, births, deaths). This will confirm your caps are\cf1 
\par \cf4   sufficient and the gas budget is realistic.\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   ---\cf1 
\par 
